SIMPLE: spread
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spread
<hw>Spread</hw> <pr>(spr⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spread</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Spreading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>spreden</ets>, AS. <ets>spraedan</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>spreiden</ets>, <ets>spreijen</ets>, LG. <ets>spreden</ets>,
<ets>spreen</ets>, <ets>spreien</ets>, G. <ets>spreiten</ets>, Dan.
<ets>sprede</ets>, Sw. <ets>sprida</ets>. Cf. <er>Spray</er> water
flying in drops.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To extend in length and
breadth, or in breadth only; to stretch or expand to a broad or broader
surface or extent; to open; to unfurl; <as>as, to <ex>spread</ex> a
carpet; to <ex>spread</ex> a tent or a sail</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He bought a parcel of a field where he had <qex>spread</qex> his
tent.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxxiii. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here the Rhone⟦br⟧
Hath <qex>spread</qex> himself a couch.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To extend so as to cover something; to extend to a
great or greater extent in every direction; to cause to fill or cover a
wide or wider space.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rose, as in a dance, the stately trees, and <qex>spread</qex>⟦br⟧
Their branches hung with copious fruit.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To divulge; to publish, as news or fame; to cause to
be more extensively known; to disseminate; to make known fully; <as>as,
to <ex>spread</ex> a report; -- often accompanied by
<ex>abroad</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They, when they were departed, <qex>spread</qex> abroad his fame
in all that country.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. ix. 31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To propagate; to cause to affect great numbers;
<as>as, to <ex>spread</ex> a disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To diffuse, as emanations or effluvia; to emit;
<as>as, odoriferous plants <ex>spread</ex> their
fragrance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To strew; to scatter over a surface; <as>as, to
<ex>spread</ex> manure; to <ex>spread</ex> lime on the
ground</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To prepare; to set and furnish with provisions;
<as>as, to <ex>spread</ex> a table</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Boiled the flesh, and <qex>spread</qex> the board.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To spread cloth</b></col>, <cd>to unfurl sail.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To diffuse; propagate; disperse; publish;
distribute; scatter; circulate; disseminate; dispense.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spread</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spread
<hw>Spread</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To extend in length
and breadth in all directions, or in breadth only; to be extended or
stretched; to expand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Plants, if they <qex>spread</qex> much, are seldom tall.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Governor Winthrop, and his associates at Charlestown, had for a
church a large, <qex>spreading</qex> tree.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Trumbull.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be extended by drawing or beating; <as>as, some
metals <ex>spread</ex> with difficulty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be made known more extensively, as
news.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be propagated from one to another; <as>as, the
disease <ex>spread</ex> into all parts of the city</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spread</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spread
<hw>Spread</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Extent;
compass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have got a fine <qex>spread</qex> of improvable land.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Expansion of parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No flower hath <qex>spread</qex> like that of the woodbine.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A cloth used as a cover for a table or a
bed.</def><-- bedspread -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A table, as spread or furnished with a meal; hence,
an entertainment of food; a feast.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A privilege which one person buys of another, of
demanding certain shares of stock at a certain price, or of delivering
the same shares of stock at another price, within a time agreed
upon.</def> <mark>[Brokers' Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>An unlimited expanse of
discontinuous points.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Finance)</fld> <def>An arbitrage transaction
operated by buying and selling simultaneously in two separate markets,
as Chicago and New York, when there is an abnormal difference in price
between the two markets. It is called a <col><b>back
spread</b></col>when the difference in price is less than the normal
one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Gems)</fld> <def>Surface in proportion to the depth
of a cut stone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spread</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spread
<hw>Spread</hw>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Spread</er>,
<pos>v.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spread eagle</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>An eagle with
outspread wings, the national emblem of the United States.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The figure of an eagle, with its wings elevated and its
legs extended; often met as a device upon military ornaments, and the
like.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <cd>An eagle displayed; an
eagle with the wings and legs extended on each side of the body, as in
the double-headed eagle of Austria and Russia. See <er>Displayed</er>,
2.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>spread-eagle</ent>⟦br⟧
